As you can see, the block `14238` is processed. It goes into the second leg of the if-block, outputting `inserted forked block`. Thus, it is never actually inserted as in `self.insert(block)` but written as in `self.write(block)`. The next block, `14239`, for some reason goes into the first leg, since the `Td` of that block `10438988748` is larger than `self.td` (`10438439508`). Thus, it tries to perform a `getBlockByNumber` on `14238`. If I understand correctly, however, the `write`-operation only makes it lookuppable by hash, while the `insert`-operation is required for the block to be looked-up by number:

```
func (bc *ChainManager) insert(block *types.Block) {
    key := append(blockNumPre, block.Number().Bytes()...)
    bc.blockDb.Put(key, block.Hash().Bytes())

    bc.blockDb.Put([]byte("LastBlock"), block.Hash().Bytes())
    bc.currentBlock = block
    bc.lastBlockHash = block.Hash()
}

func (bc *ChainManager) write(block *types.Block) {
    enc, err := rlp.EncodeToBytes((*types.StorageBlock)(block))
    if err != nil   {
        glog.V(logger.Error).Infof("write(block) error for block %v :%v", block,err)    
        glog.V(logger.Error).Infof("enc has value %v ", enc)        
    }

    key := append(blockHashPre, block.Hash().Bytes()...)
    bc.blockDb.Put(key, enc)
    // Push block to cache
    bc.cache.Push(block)
}
```

Thus, the lookup fails, returns `nil` and and a nullpointer crashes the app. So, from a programming-perspective I know why it fails, but I have no idea how it should be...? (I am a noob at both Go and Ethereum)
